<p class="mt-3">
    Toasts are shown imperatively through <code>IToastService</code>, which renders any component as
    the toast body and auto-dismisses it after <code>ToastOptions.Duration</code> (5 seconds by
    default). A body declares itself as a toast by inheriting <code>HBToast</code> - that base
    exposes <code>DismissAsync()</code> directly, so a close button can dismiss the toast early with
    no cascading parameter or wiring required. Showing a toast never blocks the caller - unlike a
    modal, there's no result to await.
</p>

<p>
    <code>Create&lt;TComponent&gt;()</code> starts a fluent chain: bind parameters with
    <code>WithParam(x =&gt; x.Message, "Saved")</code>, then show it with <code>Show()</code>, which
    returns the <code>IToastInstance</code> handle and optionally takes a <code>ToastOptions</code>
    for that one toast. Parameters are selected by expression, so a renamed or mistyped parameter is
    a compile error rather than a dictionary key that silently binds nothing. <code>Show&lt;TComponent&gt;(parameters)</code>
    still takes a dictionary directly when the parameters are only known at runtime.
</p>

